Inferential statistics

Normal Distribution

Sample means for Math Score

Sample means for Reading Score

Sample means for Writing Score

  • The data is normally distributed in math, reading, and writing score in both population and sample means
  • the sample mean \(\bar{x}\) is an unbiased estimator for the underlying population mean \(\mu\)
  • the sample means \(\bar{x}\) are centered on the population mean \(\mu\)

95% CI

Math score

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  student$math.score
## t = 0, df = 999, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 66.089
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  65.14806 67.02994
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##    66.089

There is a 95% chance that interval [65.14806, 67.02994] covers the true population parameter \(\mu\) (66.089).

Probability

The probability for the students to get more than 50 in math is 85%

The probability for the students to get more than 50 in writing is 87.6%

The probability for the students to get more than 50 in reading is 90.3%

Two sample t-test

Is there a relationship between gender and scores in each subject?

\(\bar{x}_{female} - \bar{x}_{male}\)

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  math.score by gender
## t = -5.398, df = 997.98, p-value = 8.421e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -6.947209 -3.242813
## sample estimates:
## mean in group female   mean in group male 
##             63.63320             68.72822

Here the p-value = 8.421e-08 which means:

  • Reject the null hypothesis
  • There is evidence that the gender is related to the scores in math
  • We can use the gender to predict scores in math!
